<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96712913325823></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96712913325823><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96712913325823>Crowd control strategies:</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96712913325823#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=353><span id=Sage>Tehom</span></a>, <span id=Sage>Sage</span><br><span id=notbold>135 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Thu, Aug 24th 10:58 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[2.67]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Crowd control strategies are among the most varied and complicated in the game. They can change not just every level, but depending on the zone you're in, the group you're in, the skill of the players, the nature of a pull, and the current health and mana of a group. One of the greatest dangers an enchanter faces is imagining that the same tactics she has employed before will are the best tactics to use in other situations. I thought I might start a thread on how people handle different situations - without getting buried in minutiae, we might be able to come up with a list of guidelines and principles on which people can formulate their strategies.<br><br>For example, I'll start with the three pull. Under what circumstances do you individually mez the other two, AE mez the lot then charm one to use on the primary target, root two, charm one of the rooted and have them fight in the background, or just keep the other two AE mezzed?<br>&nbsp;<br></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
	   </form></table><ul>
<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=970479953966></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f970479953966><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=970479953966>RE: Crowd control strategies:</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=970479953966#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Mon, Oct 2nd 5:45 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Default<span id=notbold>[2.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>The two pull scenario.<br>With a good group I will target the weaker MoB and enthrall them and Mem Blur them (don't like it when they agro me) then med until they are ready or MoB breaks.&nbsp;&nbsp;If it is a higher level MoB I will debuff or if I am in a small group.  If they are both casters I will tend to use Stun series instead so my party don't get hit.<br>The three pull scenario.<br>Almost never use AoE mes or charm although I am starting to see the merrits of it now.  I prefer to pick off the lose MoB's using enthrall/mem blur and then medding or melee depending on group.  Again if there are more than one caster I will either stun all or use stun DD's on the one they are fighting or better still drag party back from group of MoB's and stun or whirl from there.  Casters can make short work of your party if you let them and put undue pressure on the Healer if you have one.<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
