<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=9678428603937></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f9678428603937><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=9678428603937>RE: Crowd control strategies:</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=9678428603937#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=1229><span id= >Tashim</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Sep 1st 5:14 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.50]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Myself, I consider AE mez to be sloppy, messy, and unprofessional.<br>It is not without drawbacks, (like short duration, risk of self mez, etc)<br>However, with that said, I always (unless fighting things immune to it, like giants) keep it ready.<br><br>I only use it in a few circumstances.<br>1- To escape.&nbsp;&nbsp;AE mez can often give a good head start when "Run like hell" is called for.  Also, AE mez can give enough time to get even a slow evac off.  (hell, once I even gave a druid enough time to sit, *memorize* the evac, and cast it before anyone died) I recommend using stuns to help with this also.<br><br>2- To prevent death.  If my group can't sustain the damage from the opponents in the time it would take me to mez each one individually, then AE mez is needed.  The exact number will vary, depending on how tough/ready your group is vs. how tough the opponents are. How quickly you can target mobs is also a factor.   For an example, when I was younger, (and, generally thought I knew everything) I would AE mez pulls or trains of 4 or more.  Now that I am old (and hopefully wiser) I find that I don't need to AE mez until there are about 8 or so.<br><br>3- When charming.  I can AE mez a group of mobs, charm one, have my pet assist whoever it should, then AE mez again.  This uses the short duration of the AE mez to your advantage, as the idea is for the mez to break before the charm does.  You re-mez everything so that only your pet breaks.  (The second mez will not affect your pet, but it will refresh the mez on everything else.)<br><br>A few other notes, when using AE mez:<br>In order to keep from mesmerizing yourself, you can do 4 things:<br>1- Don't cast it close to you.  Center it on party members than know not to stand close to you, and to stand in the middle of the fray.  Healers can do this *very* well, as this uses the taunt from their heal (which can taunt many mobs at once) to your advantage. I recommend a good stiff drink before tryin' this.   ;)<br><br>2- High magic resist.  Resistance is a game of dice, but you can slant the odds.<br><br>3- Lower charisma.  Yup, you heard me.  lower charisma.  If you are fighting things that /con blue to you and/or have low magic resistance anyway, odds are, you don't need that 200 charisma to affect them reliably.  It can be darn hard to resist yourself when you are beautiful.<br><br>4- Have 15 buffs already.  If you don't have room for the mez buff, then it can't affect you.  This is my personal favorite, as it also helps protect from poisons and diseases. Watch for things that overwrite buffs.  Root will override SoW, but if you have 15 buffs and no SoW, then you can't be rooted either.  Some diseases that weaken will overwrite strength buffs.  Slow spells will overwrite speed buffs.<br>&nbsp;<br>Tashim<br>Keeper of the Wyrd</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 >&nbsp;</td><td align=right valign=bottom>
	   <span style='font-weight: normal; font-size: 9px;'>[<a href=#top>Top</a>]</span></tr>
