<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96726119522224></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96726119522224><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96726119522224>RE: Crowd control strategies:</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=13&mid=96726119522224#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=508><span id= >Sobur</span></a>, <span id= > </span><br><span id=notbold>6 posts</td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 25th 11:39 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Excellent<span id=notbold>[5.00]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>A lot also depends on how big your group is in those situations.... Also what the MoB types are... Are they all warriors, all casters, a mix of the two...<br>If it is just you and a warrior you would want to keep them stunned and not use root to minimize the chance of extra damage by the rooted MoB. You never want to root a caster MoB. It won't stop them from putting a hurt on you and your group. <br>If you have a bigger group root is good on a melee MoB as it is less aggro intensive so the MoB can be taunted off you much easier...<br>The list is endless with to many possibilities to be contained in a single post, and different people like to handle things in different ways...<br>The best advice is to experiment with your spells so you know what to expect from them and then learn what your group will do in certain situations. When you can anticiapate what the MoB and your group is going to do, you become a god :)<br>&nbsp;<br>Sobur<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;Dying with style, in a zone near you...</td></tr>
